postcontent: If you can read this, the pistol is still available.  I will deactivate when sold.  I WILL SHIP TO A C&R OR 01 FFL, shipping would be $15 more or less via USPS Priority. No Imports marks, a GI bring back.  A nice example of the Italian Military Model 1935, made by and for the Wehrmacht.  The 4UT (Quatro Ufficio tecnico di Contolo Armie Muzioni) mark in a circle on the right tang indicates Army use.  After Mussolini was ousted the Germans took control of the Gardone area and the Beretta plant.  Needing any weapons they could get, they did away with the high polish finish and produced this phosphate finished gun.  Bore is very good to excellent with smooth shiny lands and good rifling.  I have fired this and it functions fine.  I've owned this for a number of years and it's been sitting in my safe, cleaned and lubed, but it's a duplicate and I should thin things out.  Built like a tank, these Nazi Beretta pistols were basic but very effective.  The "Pistols of the German Wehrmacht" web site shows a very similar gun with a fairly close serial number in similar condition.

title: For Sale:  Truly Excellent Condition Old Commie Gun - CZ-52   7.62 x.25 Pistol w2 mags and holster w/ammo (if local sale)
postcontent: I have a soft spot for this particular model.  It was my first firearm.  Way back when, while I was in the Army, I picked up a few of these.  At the time I thought it would be cool to own a gun that was designed to kill me (designed to penetrate the old steel pot helmets).  The Tokarev Round has significantly more penetrating power then a .357 magnum.  So powerful that some ranges will only let you shot it on the rifle range.  What a hoot to shoot.  A real bushwacker.  Took this particular pistol in recently on trade.  Looks very clean and finish is well over 95%.   Numbers matching.  If this goes as a local sale, I will throw in a box of the surplus ammo shown in the pics.  I have no idea how the ammo was stored, or if it is a full box.  Sure looks and feels as if full.    Box says 72 rounds.    I used to shoot this same ammo type, so I know it is corrosive.  Don't let that scare you.  That is all that I ever shot in mine, and the bore looked as good as new when I finally sold it years later, with probably several thousand rounds through it.  With corrosive ammo, just remember to rinse out the barrel as soon as you get home from the range (easy to field strip).  Dry the barrel with hair dryer and then do a general cleaning and oil it up.  This is a great gun to shoot.  Price is firm.  Marked as 1953 model.
